TY  - JOUR
TI  - Clinician assessment of an in situ peripheral intravenous catheter: Using ultrasound to prevent unrecognized extravasation.
AU  - Bailey, Jonathan G.
AU  - Dumbarton, Tristan
AU  - D'Souza, Brandon
AU  - Kiberd, Mathew B.
JO  - Vascular Access
AB  - In the perioperative setting, functioning peripheral intravenous catheter (PIVC) access is essential for safe fluid and medication delivery. However, peripheral intravenous infiltration and extravasation (PIVIE) events occur in 16% to 78% of cases, posing a significant risk to patient safety. These events are often difficult to diagnose, especially when symptoms, such as pain on injection, localized edema, and erythema, mimic those of a normally functioning catheter, particularly after prolonged dwell time. This paper presents a comprehensive approach to assessing PIVC reliability through a combination of physical examination and advanced ultrasound techniques. Static and dynamic ultrasound methods, including the saline flush test and colour Doppler imaging, are reviewed for their effectiveness in detecting interstitial or malfunctioning PIVCs. These techniques improve diagnostic accuracy, especially in pediatric and critical care populations. Emerging adjunctive technologies, such as bioimpedance monitoring and optical sensors, are also discussed as potential tools for real-time assessment. When integrated with clinical judgment, ultrasound may enhance the precision of PIVC evaluation, allowing clinicians to distinguish between functional and compromised lines. Early identification of interstitial catheters can reduce patient discomfort, prevent complications, and avoid unnecessary catheter replacements. Overall, this paper advocates for the routine use of ultrasound in combination with physical assessment to optimize PIVC management and improve outcomes in the perioperative environment.
