TY  - JOUR
TI  - Long peripheral catheters: A viable option for the neonatal intensive care unit.
AU  - Gonzalez, Leanne D.
AU  - Rodriguez-Warren, Dinorah
JO  - Vascular Access
AB  - Purpose: Vascular access is needed to provide intravenous (IV) hydration, fluid boluses, nutrition, and medications to neonatal intensive care unit (NICU) patients. Although peripheral intravenous catheters (PIVCs) are the most common vascular access devices, the life expectancy of a PIVC is short-lived, ranging from 1 to 1.5 days, as documented (Helm et al., 2015). The short lifespan of PIVCs can lead to increased venous depletion as it may take several punctures to obtain a successful cannulation or the insertion of a peripheral intravenous central catheter (PICC). The increased insertion of short-term PICCs warranted a quality improvement project to investigate another option for venous access. Long peripheral catheters (LPCs) used in neonates have reduced the need for central catheter insertions and can be considered a viable option for this population. Methods: A quality improvement project implemented the Plan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA) framework using LPCs to decrease short-term PICCs by 25%. Inclusion criteria were neonates weighing ≥ 1,500 grams who required IV fluids and/or medication therapy for five to seven days or neonates who experienced multiple unsuccessful peripheral intravenous insertion attempts. Results: Forty-nine LPCs were inserted, and eight patients received more than one LPC for therapy. The longest dwell time of 24 days occurred in an ex-22-week-old infant, corrected to 26 weeks. Among the LPCs inserted, there was a total of 190 days of dwell. The number of PICCs for short-term therapies decreased by 25%, which prevented 238 venipunctures and promoted vein preservation. Conclusion: The NICU team members advocated for LPC placement over PICCs, which resulted in a decrease in the minimum weight inclusion criterion. Despite the success of vein preservation, future projects are needed based on LPC insertion in neonates of lower weights, the use of ultrasound guidance, the number of venipunctures before LPC placement, the knowledge of the NICU provider regarding LPC placement, and the validation of proficiency of different LPC devices.
